ing medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":53,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":62,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":73,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Maud Fitzgeffry was born after 1495, in Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, her father, John Fitzgeoffrey, was 8525 and her mother, Countess Of Sussex Maude de Saint Hilaire, was 8524. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Foster. She died in Lady, Seine-et-Marne, France."},"et":{"after 1495–":"pärast 1495–Surnud","1495–Female":"1495–Surnud","1490–1555":"1490–1555","1520–1578":"1520–1578","1475–Male":"1475–Surnud","1475–Female":"1475–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1578":"1578","1555":"1555","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1495":"1495","after 1495":"pärast 1495","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England","Lady, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Lady, Seine-et-Marne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"after 1495–":"1495 jälkeen–Kuollut","1495–Female":"1495–Kuollut","1490–1555":"1490–1555","1520–1578":"1520–1578","1475–Male":"1475–Kuollut","1475–Female":"1475–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1578":"1578","1555":"1555","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1495":"1495","after 1495":"1495 jälkeen","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England","Lady, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Lady, Seine-et-Marne, Ranska"},"fr":{"after 1495–":"après 1495–Décédée","1495–Female":"1495–Décédée","1490–1555":"1490–1555","1520–1578":"1520–1578","1475–Male":"1475–Décédé","1475–Female":"1475–Décédée","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1578":"1578","1555":"1555","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1495":"1495","after 1495":"après 1495","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, Angleterre","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, Angleterre","Lady, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Fr